This doesn't do the right thing anymore, and I think that demonstrates why racy monkey patching is a bad idea.  Consider what happens if you import this, monkey patch eventlet, then call execute (the use case I believe this is trying to address).

1) You import processutils, and thus the stdlib time module.
2) You monkey patch, including the time module
3) You call execute, which looks at the eventlet monkey patching status and sees that it was done.  Therefore it uses the eventlet version of subprocess.
4) You've now mixed stdlib time and eventlet subprocess, which is what this check is intended to avoid.

Basically the only correct thing to do is monkey patch first or not at all.  Anything else can lead to mismatches and weird bugs."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-02-05 17:08:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Actually, looking again I think my scenario above is not accurate either.  It's looking at the actual time module when checking for monkey patching, so it would probably recognize that the stdlib time was imported in the first place.  That still leaves us using stdlib time and subprocess in a monkey patched application though, which is still incorrect behavior."}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 14:25:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ben:

> 1) You import processutils, and thus the stdlib time module.

> 2) You monkey patch, including the time module 

> 3) You call execute, which looks at the eventlet monkey patching status and sees that it was done. Therefore it uses the eventlet version of subprocess. 

> 4) You've now mixed stdlib time and eventlet subprocess, which is what this check is intended to avoid.

I believe 4 is incorrect. There is only one imported time module. Monkeypatching modifies that time module. So upon execute, time will show up as monkeypatched and we will get the correct subprocess. All importing, and thus all monkeypatching (including the previously imported time module) will have happened before any execute is called."}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 14:33:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I believe this should work fine. Possible simplification mentioned in-line that I'd like considered, but not absolutely necessary. So this is a very tentative -1, and could easily turn into a +1 (especially since I could always be wrong, this stuff gets complicated)"}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 15:10:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 15:17:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 15:22:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-02-06 15:32:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Terry, see my second comment.  I realize that the final point was incorrect, but this is still not doing the right thing.  And I still think the approach is flawed in general - we shouldn't be enabling racy monkey patching, we should be fixing it in the consuming applications.  Anything else is a recipe for trouble."}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 15:54:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ben:
> That still leaves us using stdlib time and subprocess in a monkey patched application though.

un-monkey_patched time could never be used *from inside execute* in a monkey_patched application because that application would be monkey_patching 'time' before execute would ever be called.

1) Modle imports processutils, unpatched time is imported and cached
2) Import some module that monkey_patches time -> cached version for all imported modules is now monkey_patched.
3) Call execute(), subprocess is now imported at runtime, not load time. All load/import-time patching is complete. The check can see that time was monkey_patched and imports the correct subprocess.

The only thing that would break this would be if someone did something crazy like calling monkey_patch() inside a function that was called after calling execute(), then calling execute() again."}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-02-06 16:32:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ben: an example of what I'm talking about:

https://gist.github.com/otherwiseguy/5e7032da7d1326d10d80

notice that if you run use_unpatched_and_patched(), we still see that the check to time shows it is monkey_patched()."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-16 18:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-02-20 18:14:20.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Agreed that there are better ways to handle eventlet in projects.'}]

commit_message:
processutils: postpone eventlet monkey patching check

We should not check whether time module is monkey patched during import
since in that case we force our consumers to maintain some specific
import order, which is sometimes hard or impossible.

Instead of checking during import, do it on demand when execute() is
actually issued.

Change-Id: Ic465c343cd3cc9144127ee5dd11714bdde300a42
Closes-Bug: #1418541

commit_message:
sanity_check: introduce magic to easily add new version checks

Introduce a new version.Checker() class that may be used as a callable
for sanity checks. It introspects neutron.cmd.sanity.checks module and
handles all common operations (comparing versions, handling exceptions,
logging errors), allowing to easily add more version based checks.

The only things that a developer needs to provide now to add a new
version check is one function (get_%name_version) and a new entry in
AVAILABLE_CHECKS.

Also made dnsmasq version check to use the new class.

Relocated all version related code into neutron.cmd.sanity.version.

Co-Authored-By: Sridhar Gaddam <sridhar.gaddam@enovance.com>
Change-Id: I5615070e335f8e23fc22dd5e7b1af6bb57979e16

commit_message:
Add invalid "get_*_(list|show)" pattern to T108

Most list methods' names are "list_<resource name>s" but some methods
are "get_<resource name>_list" now. In addition, a method name is
"get_<resource name>_show" and duplicated meanings. This patch adds
them as invalid method names to T108 rule and renames some methods
for consistent names.

Change-Id: I2b0ecfec4554dd82f5ecd292c9eb597c37eed37f

commit_message:
Split resource_setup for compute volumes tests

Split up the resource_setup method for the compute volumes tests,
per the latest spec.

Partially-implements bp:resource-cleanup

Change-Id: If65a8378dbe06bf5ca4f1865bae3c67cbea75fc1

Split resource_setup for volume tests

Split up the resource_setup method for all the volume tests, as per the
latest spec.

Partially-implements bp:resource-cleanup

commit_message:
Adding api tests for dvr routers

in network_client.py:
update_router in json/network_client.py did not provide a way to update
the 'distributed' attribute of a router. Sending a rest call to a
system that does not support dvr (icehouse and older) or aa system with
dvr extension disabled will cause a failure, thus care must be taken to
only include the attribute in the rest call if it is explicitely
requested via the kwargs dict.

Tests Added:
-test_distributed_router_creation
-test_centralized_router_creation
-test_centralized_router_update_to_dvr

Change-Id: I19fb6fc260ac5aaf9b2a1456ade242bc3ee93b8d

commit_message:
Remove unused NotFound raise

get_floating_ip_details() contains NotFound raise, but the exception
would never happen because previous tempest-lib's get() raises it
if HTTP404 is gotten. So this patch removes it.

Change-Id: Ia7f18dfb7491d7379e0ab55b8f84c8b10b7ebb33

commit_message:
Enable non-voting keystoneclient functional tests

Turn on basic functional testing for keystoneclient. This will initially
import the tests from tempest.

There is currently only 1 trivial functional test so this will become
gating as soon as we can validate the configuration.

Change-Id: I256deb532f0d73bf9a6efb8c9a353a52cd1eb281

Renat, Can you provide the oslo.messaging failure you're seeing? I don't have unit tests error and Jenkins verified this fine. If it's unit test related and it needs monkey_patch, maybe do that in the base test module?  The reason why I remove that from the mistral __init__.py is because when I deploy to Apache with multi-process/threads, apache complains about gevent not able to switch thread.  I can post the exact error message when I get into office."}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2015-02-20 06:26:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Remove eventlet monkey patch in mistral __init__

Eventlet monkey patch in mistral/__init__.py leads to "unable to
switch thread" error when hosting the mistral API under apache.

Change-Id: Ib1fa4c2522a4afa0635cc9fee9fac02e610414de

commit_message:
Provide one resource for Compute v2 Limits

This change makes use of having Resources as property types and provides
one parent resource, Limits, to interact with the /limits REST API. As
this response body contains two different types of limits with two
different structures, it offers Limits.absolute and Limits.rate, which
replace the two separate resources that currently exist that require two
API calls to work with. Limits.absolute is an AbsoluteLimits instance,
and Limits.rate is a list of RateLimit instances.

The interaction would now work as follows:

my_limits = limits.Limits().get(session)
print(my_limits.absolute.server_meta) # 128 by default
for limits in my_limits.rate: # iterate over URIs with limits
    print(limits.uri) # prints "*/servers"
    for limit in limits:
        print(limit) # print the specific rate limits on this URI

Change-Id: I5363d2e39dcc57f9fd164ec88ab5b79abeaa18ed
Closes-Bug: 1422057

commit_message:
Fail main maven build if java maven build fails

Java maven sub build could fail and main maven build still
succeed because of the shell script in between. Pass the maven
exit code back

Change-Id: I4df4ee7d782db21c89c49b0ee0a4741cbfa97edb

commit_message:
purge all pure python libraries

python libraries should be installed from upstream, not from the
distro, as much as possible. The following is a first attempt at
purging all the python libraries and making it so that they instead
should fall back to the pypi versions.

Libraries which are known to include native code are left behind.

Change-Id: I47b7e787771683c2fc4404e586f11c1a19aac15c

commit_message:
Revamp README file

The README used only python-*client objects, thus defeating the
purpose of shade, which is about putting a facade for all those
interfaces to simplify things.
README now shows you can use shade simplified interface and also
access the underlying python-*client API objects.

Change-Id: I0c638beab615177fc6ce3704c5443a3394a87ed0

commit_message:
Consistent names of args and metavars, and help strings

This modifies the CLI so that the argument names, metavar names
and help strings are more consistent.

Argument names that consist of more than one word are now separated
by hyphens instead of underscores. Existing argument names with
underscores are still supported but not displayed via help. The new
argument names are: http_method -> http-method, chassis_uuid -> chassis,
driver_info -> driver-info, node_uuid -> node.

Metavars are only used in the help strings displayed to the user. For
consistency, they are lowercased with hyphens to separate the
words. (Using spaces might make someone think that more than one argument
is needed.)

Help strings were updated. Among other things, they are treated like
sentences with the first letter in upper case, and a period at the end.

Closes-Bug: #1420318
Change-Id: If05d51b09d787ccfbf6f6d35d8e752d42f673601

Added new hook to copy files

* added new hook to copy files and test
* after migrating generating and uploading keys into tasks
  we can remove predeployment actions for this tasks

commit_message:
Rename oslo_release.sh to library_release.sh

Rename oslo_release.sh and update its internal documentation to make it
more suitable for use by libraries maintained outside of Oslo.

Change-Id: Ida01b1cb2a6d3c8da529532bc4372c2d80ae4ad1

commit_message:
Reinstate the devstack-dsvm-cells job for novaclient

A recent release of a novaclient broke several projects which
gate on the devstack-dsvm-cells job. This change adds the job
back to novaclient.

Related-Bug: #1423695

Change-Id: I435036cce2382bb0b4596d4a1b19e98885e92702

commit_message:
Fix index name in downgrade 26b54cf9024d migration

In downgrade of migration 26b54cf9024d_add_index_on_allocated is
trying to drop index 'ix_ml2_vxlan_allocations_allocated',
which is not exits.

Closes-bug: #1421618

Change-Id: I4c75e78512cc6d112a23ab5c7de6e8ca104891b0

commit_message:
Add vCenter driver instance name section

Add instance name section to VMware configuration reference.
KVM use instance_template name but VMware vCenter driver
use instance ID.

Change-Id: I325b5282dfdbe1b71657c4043644b5641cb7320f
Closes-Bug: #1379682

commit_message:
Improve List Role Assignment Tests

Add new tests to role_assignments API.
Filters + effective mode are combined in order to
cover all allowed and forbidden cases.

Closes-Bug: 1396083

Change-Id: Ia076539b6099bd32ff3f8e3ee6930b7ecb9bbd7b

commit_message:
fix for _get_external_device_interface_name trace

On removal of external gateway from DVR the code path
external_gateway_removed(...) was trying to access the
agent gateway port interface even when no fip namespace exists.
This change checks for existence of namespace before
accessing the agent gateway port interface through
_get_external_device_interface_name(...) or looking for
floating ips that may have been configured on the
port.

Change-Id: Idcf28ff93f16f1d692fe7acb678fb90aabe5af5e
Closes-Bug: #1421497

commit_message:
[install-guide] do not synchronize Neutron DB on openSUSE/SLES

It is not necessary to manually synchronize the Neutron DB on
openSUSE/SLES because neutron-manage-db is part of the
init file.

Change-Id: I4a9f7fa37de58449e764a3d1bd24b7ed663c8eef
Partial-Bug: 1422281
Backport: Juno

Andrei, thanks for your comments. But the manager (different implementations) code calls into the driver code immediately. I thought it's actually better to fix it at the driver level at one place instead of fixing it at multiple different implementations of managers."}, {'account_id': 8863, 'date': '2015-02-18 20:43:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It can be fixed just in one place https://github.com/stackforge/magnetodb/blob/master/magnetodb/storage/manager/simple_impl.py
If internal name does not exist we can be sure that driver has not enouph information to perform this operation. So it should be handled on manager level'}, {'account_id': 11006, 'date': '2015-02-18 21:01:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think we need to update both https://github.com/stackforge/magnetodb/blob/master/magnetodb/storage/manager/simple_impl.py and https://github.com/stackforge/magnetodb/blob/master/magnetodb/storage/manager/async_simple_impl.py

Since they both immediately call into storage driver, why not update driver layer and the code can be future proof if more manager implementation is introduced.'}, {'account_id': 8863, 'date': '2015-02-18 21:21:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

https://github.com/stackforge/magnetodb/blob/master/magnetodb/storage/manager/async_simple_impl.py is inherited from simple_impl
I suggest to add check to 'delete_table' method in simple_imple, table_info is available there"}, {'account_id': 11006, 'date': '2015-02-18 21:26:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Andrei for the explanation. However, we will need to update the _do_delete_table though, which is overriden in async_simple_impl.py.'}, {'account_id': 8601, 'date': '2015-02-19 12:34:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

But the manager (different implementations) code calls into the driver code immediately - it is not true. we can call driver via Rabbitmq and it is not immidietly I guess.
If we will move this code to delete_table method of simple_impl module we can skip this redudant RPC call of async-table-manager. And I agree with Andrew that we can do it in one place, in simple_imple, before _do_delete_table call'}, {'account_id': 11006, 'date': '2015-02-19 19:00:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 11006, 'date': '2015-02-19 19:05:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ok, added check in simple_impl.py and also preserved check in storage driver code to make it future proof (if some storage manager doesn't follow or override behavior of simple_impl.py.

Also added unit tests for 3 test scenarios:
- table create failed and does not exist
- table delete failed but table exists
- table delete failed and table does not exist"}, {'account_id': 8863, 'date': '2015-02-19 19:45:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add check for non-existing table internal name for delete table

This change added check for non-existing internal name for tables
which caused exception when trying to delete table in CREATE_FAILED
or DELETE_FALED status if table internal name does not exist.

Change-Id: I3175a364a4e678f35b860db26f9dec999997f8a0
Closes-bug: #1422908

> I don't think there are any projects (Nova included) that use init_default_lvm_volume any longer

lib/nova has 

 if [[ "$NOVA_BACKEND" == "LVM" ]]; then
    init_default_lvm_volume_group
 fi

so i'd just like to clarify if this is right or not.  if its not needed, we should remove the whole lot'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-02-17 20:20:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-02-18 20:54:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Ian
Suppose that's fine but quite frankly I don't know why that should be a part of this patch.  This patch is explicitly to remove the call to the create in cinder setup.  Frankly I don't care if there's an unused method left behind, but think it's fine to pull that out as a separate patch.

If this is really important for some reason I can amend this change to remove it entirely but personally that doesn't seem like the right thing."}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-02-18 20:56:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Ian,
Ok, prevous comment made no sense.  As you pointed out, YES nova still uses that; so NO it should not be removed entirely.

My proposed patch is to remove it only from Cinder init which sets a group name based on be_name.  

Sorry for any confusion.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-02-18 21:37:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

ok, so to further clarify lib/lvm and especially the comments around init_default_lvm_volume_group all talk about cinder & nova sharing the volume group; comments which I guess are now actually incorrect since cinder is using the be_* volumes.  so while we don't need to re-write the world, we should just clean up lib/lvm's comments to reflect the reality"}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-02-18 21:38:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

sorry, see above'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-02-19 02:13:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Ian
So turns out Dean had some insight that the "shared nova/cinder" add was fairly recent to try and reduce the disk usage on test instances.  Problem is that the way the Cinder lib is right now it actually has the opposite effect and creates a VG that is never used.

There is work that needs to be done here to clean all of this up and sort it out a bit better, however from the perspective of this change it really is unrelated IMO.  I'm perfectly fine if this doesn't merge, it doesn't hurt anything as it is now but it does cause some confusion and is creating a VG that is never used (at least by the gate).'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-02-20 15:34:38.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Don't create stack-volume-default in lib/cinder

In the past lib/cinder would always call
init_default_lvm_volume_group which would use the
/lib/lvm default VG name of stack-volumes-default.
We switched over to using the be_type and be_name
to create and use stack-volume-lvmdriver-X, but we
now have both calls in place.

The result is that we have two VG's, one on the loop
device named stack-volumes-default which actually
isn't used by the Cinder tests, and another on
/dev/vdX that's actually the intended Cinder VG.

To reiterate, the current gate tests are in fact only
using the stack-volumes-lvmdrver-X VG.

Closes-Bug: #1422532

Change-Id: I8e8b40f1d0d1ad7be0f9abf210ab1ea52c7468a3

commit_message:
Make Default value for Groups column translatable.


Here we are passing a default string 'False' to empty_value, which is not
translatable as we haven't used the function ugettext().
So to make it translatable we are using this function.

Closes-Bug: #1399308
Change-Id: Ie568118ad702fbbe80b4ae26fbc863524037342c

commit_message:
Reduce logstash and elasticsearch memory heap size for AIO

This patch reduces the memory heap size for the elasticsearch and
logstash services for the AIO build. This is for the purpose of
improving the reliability of gate commit checks.

Closes-Bug: #1423242
Change-Id: I614ac2a3985ba002fe7de0a1704731a44a8928bc

commit_message:
Nova changes required for standalone EC2 API implementation

Some of the information required for EC2 API, currently supported by
existing nova's EC2 API implemenation is not exposed by public
nova APIs. This spec lists these omissions and provides suggestions
about how to expose them.

APIImpact
Implements: blueprint ec2-api

Change-Id: I4102808405fef420f159dcbd46293f50cec56f0f

commit_message:
Retry installing apt packages by default

There are a number of tasks used to install apt packages. Some of the
tasks will retry on failure and others will not. These tasks are
susceptible to failure and so it makes sense that they retry if the
task fails.

This commit updates the apt tasks so that they all retry with the
default retries and delay values of 3 and 5 respectively. In addition
all the tasks will attempt to update the cache if it is older than
600 seconds.

Some of the apt tasks had the state set to latest, this has been
changed to present because upgrades should be handled by specific
upgrade tasks.

Closes-Bug: #1421238
Change-Id: I8c20c5c0a2ce87706a99734adcdf55c93efb405c
(cherry picked from commit 19f86f4c00099d5994d77a9fe8f431d9373b15a5)

commit_message:
Add retry and fallback server capability to apt-key tasks

This patch adds retries (with a delay) to the common and
container_common apt-key tasks, then also includes an optional retry
using a fallback keyserver for the appropriate tasks.

The patch also removes the conditional for the platform version as it is
not entirely relevant at this stage - the whole environment is only
tested to work on Ubuntu 14.04 anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1423123
Change-Id: Ica590a61319f60beaa8c6d6f4b8210400efca922
(cherry picked from commit 16c2a5fc4a13481433e091598bb19009b5d3683e)

commit_message:
Add Measurements section to Telemetry Admin Guide

Add a new section to the admin guide of Telemetry to list the available
metrics and other metrics related information. This patch adds the base
file, which will contain the references for the  tables with some general
information about the metrics stored in Telemetry.

Change-Id: I085af5818ca90497144de5b1a70dbfa939cd7ccc

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Add missing database create steps for sahara

Added missing database create step so that later schema update steps will not fail.

Change-Id: Iaf383430055ece3e83f9d7de8b518f5ee4f2298f
Closes-Bug: #1418654

commit_message:
Fixes Create Network & Subnet Modals

This reverts some CSS changes added by
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/137417/ which break the Create
Network modal, as well as the Create and Edit Subnet modals.

Specifically:
- Removes the unnecessary scroll bar
- Realigns modal on the page
- Fixes workflow tab alignment

Change-Id: I15fa29781e4bc3a400a5599e083ec24ec93fe188
Closes-Bug: 1423888

commit_message:
Glance image delete output

Deleting an already deleted image using admin user is throwing an
error "404 Not Found" which is confusing. Deleting an image that does
not exist throws "No image with a name or ID of 'image-id' exists."

Updated the code so that trying to delete an already deleted image
throws "No image with an ID of 'image-id' exists." error.

Closes-Bug: #1333119
Change-Id: I8f9a6174663337a0f48aafa029a4339c32eb2134
Co-Authored-By: Abhishek Talwar <abhishek.talwar@tcs.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

We actually shouldn't do anything here. As a library, we just enable the ability to log messages, which we already do. Users of the library should enable their own handlers which will receive our messages within the proper format.

    import logging
    logging.basicConfig(filename='python-openstacksdk.log',level=logging.DEBUG, format='%(asctime)s %(levelname)s: %(name)s %(message)s')

commit_message:
Add logging functionality to openstack.utils

This change moves the ability to enable logging out of the
examples.common module and into the openstack.utils since it is
generally useful.

This is intended to give users a short-term solution to receive
debugging messages. If they want to always have our messages logged in
their application they should create their own logging handler(s) with
their own format, and that will cause our messages to be sent to their
handlers as they wish.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-openstacksdk/+bug/1418307 is open to
track the documentation aspect of this.

Change-Id: Ic8768d529d0389b9b04bd4ea31453a82f30faf33

commit_message:
Add OSTF tests for Glance component

- Added base class for Glance component in OSTF.
- Added 'Image Create, Update, Delete' and 'List Images' tests for
  Glance api v1 and Glance api v2
- Updated requirements: added python-glanceclient=>0.14.1
- Added initialization of glance_client v1 and v2 in nmanager.py

Partially implements: blueprint ostf-and-system-tests-for-glance

Change-Id: I4a2957eefb98d718e7fc25153a6b07251250f4d2

I don't understand how I could apply the items described here when creating a new API. For example, I believe it would be easier to understand language like the following:

> APIs should be designed in a manner that supports the creation of multiple clients, potentially in a variety of languages. Reference API specifications should be defined in terms of the HTTP requests and responses. Augmenting examples may appear in other languages or syntaxes, such as CURL, and are even encouraged especially when target users are known to use those tools. However, these examples should not be used to introduce new information about the API call which is not previously defined in terms of the underlying HTTP request and response.

It would make sense for other topics to reference the general of language-neutrality. For example, we could include something like this as a *specific* guideline which was motivated by the general goal. Note that this is simply an example of how a topic might be worded; one could easily argue that it belongs in a separate change request and I would likely agree.

> To improve support for languages and libraries using standard URI templating functionality, query parameters should be named using the restricted set of "varchar" characters defined in RFC 6570 2.3, without requiring the use of percent-encoded octets.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-29 11:09:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the comments Sam.

I'm not wed to the style of language I used in the bullet points I gave, but I can explain why I did it the way I did, which might help get us to the right place.

My goal was not to create detailed actionable steps but rather to give some human narrative that gets implementors in the right frame of mind. I think far too often it is possible to make something that follows all the rules to the letter, and entirely misses the spirit. So my hope was that by having a general guidelines section we could help frame the spirit that we desire each API to embody. Then more specific documents could give details on ways and means to reach some of that spirit.

The more direct statement of what I was going for in the second point is: Imagine a human might try to type requests to the API."}, {'account_id': 8505, 'date': '2014-10-29 12:40:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree with the topic page, and also with the first point. However, I don't feel like the second point has the desired effect. Could that point be moved to a separate review request, and this one be trimmed down to just the topic page and first point?"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-29 12:44:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

See my response to the curl guideline for more thoughts in this area but "encouraging a thousand flowers to bloom" is _exactly_ what I think the "general.rst" document should be about. The other documents are about the specific and actionable technical aspects (which response code to use when, what representations, how to handle asynchronous tasks). My hope with this document was that it could be, intentionally, about hand wavey aspects of and attitudes to "quality".

Why? a) Because making good APIs is hard and some human narrative on what's good helps make it less hard, b) Because these are guidelines; they are not a spec.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-11-20 15:54:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I like the idea of corralling all of the hand-wavy stuff in one place, combined with pointers or examples of specific supported or discouraged practices it gets the reader into a similar frame of mind.

Additional sub-sections could also include rationale and the recorded debate for the more contentious guidelines or why-do-we questions, for example, a summary of the paging wars would be good to help new contributors come up to speed and not re-visit it all over yet again.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2014-11-20 16:36:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add a "general" section

This is for topics which do not easily fit into specific topics but
are more about overall style or general attitude of approach.

For an initial proposal, diversity of clients seems a good
guideline.

six==1.8.0

We should bump the *minimal* version only if it's a blocker for a project. Not just 'nice to have' or 'we test against it anyway'. The point is to communicate to downstream distributions whether they need to bump their versions, or they are ok to stick to old and proved release if they don't see another reason to bump their versions. The fewer updates to requirements the better."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-20 13:49:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Taskflow would like to use the 'raise_from' helper that
abstracts out python 3.x raise from syntax so that taskflow
can raise exceptions that operate better and are
formatted correctly (when chained) on python 3.x.

That release also fixes other issue(s) that affect openstack

commit_message:
Bump six up to 1.9.0

Taskflow would like to use the 'raise_from' helper that
abstracts out python 3.x raise from syntax so that taskflow
can raise exceptions that operate better and are
formatted correctly (when chained) on python 3.x.

That release also fixes other issue(s) that affect openstack
projects (one key one being):

- Fix `six.moves` race condition in multi-threaded code.

Change-Id: I9f4d512105fe695c68b5c4d2fcd1a405fe9b8554

commit_message:
Correctly rebuild the PXE file during takeover of ACTIVE nodes

During a conductor take-over, eg. from another failed conductor, it
rebuilds the PXE configuration of nodes that are mapped to it. This
calls node.driver.deploy.prepare(). However, in the PXE driver,
prepare() was not properly handling the case where it was called on a
node with an ACTIVE deploy state.

In such a situation, prepare() needs to switch from the "deploy" config
to the "boot" config.  Furthermore, the PXE boot file must specify the
node's root disk UUID.  This was previously not available outside of the
_continue_deploy() method, and so is now saved on
node.driver_internal_info when the initial deploy is completed.

Co-Authored-By: David Shrewsbury <shrewsbury.dave@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Chris Krelle <nobodycam@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I6adc65b756e22c5c78d30231187fe2e8ccf2594d
Closes-bug: #1421370

commit_message:
fix missing TOP_DIR which can break sourcing

There were a couple of places where TOP_DIR is missing when we do a
source of content in tools. Given that working directory can change
quite often during devstack, we need to always be explicit here.

Change-Id: I14b5699637d7f5db745bccf116f440cdcbaa8d91

commit_message:
Rename checks to fixture and update requirements

This renamed the "checks" module to be in line with other oslo libraries,
and adds fixtures and mock to the list of requirements, since they are
required for actual library code.

Change-Id: I782762d5cd4166893593e172f49fda8ab35e478d

[{'created': '2015-02-19 21:00:40.000000000', 'message': 'Sync default-setting change from Nova

Make obj_set_defaults() more useful

This makes obj_set_defaults() not overwrite existing values set on the object
with the default. The idea of obj_set_defaults() is to allow filling in fields
with default values if they are otherwise unknown. Before this patch, the
following code would not work, but does after:

 obj = MyObject(foo=123)
 obj.obj_set_defaults()
 # obj.foo would be overwritten with the default

Change-Id: Id5cfae6bc6a488ff6fab162b3d12a7412094e28e
'}]
commit_message:
Sync default-setting change from Nova

Make obj_set_defaults() more useful

This makes obj_set_defaults() not overwrite existing values set on the object
with the default. The idea of obj_set_defaults() is to allow filling in fields
with default values if they are otherwise unknown. Before this patch, the
following code would not work, but does after:

 obj = MyObject(foo=123)
 obj.obj_set_defaults()
 # obj.foo would be overwritten with the default

Change-Id: Id5cfae6bc6a488ff6fab162b3d12a7412094e28e

commit_message:
Fix configuration of Ceph-related compute options

Previously we would only configure certain Ceph-related
compute options when Ceph was used as a backend for Glance.
Using Ceph for ephemeral volumes but not for images would
result in a Puppet error. Using Ceph for volumes but not
for images would result in a sub-optimal configuration.

Change-Id: I49e83b056380b2591ade0cdb0af668f3508745d1
Closes-bug: #1405407

OpenStack public endpoints need to operate over SSL.

OpenStack public endpoints that provide APIs on public
networks need to operate over SSL.

Implements: blueprint ssl-endpoints

commit_message:
Sync obj_reset_changes(recursive=) change from Nova

Add recursive flag to obj_reset_changes()

This makes recursive resets work on sub-objects, when requested. Note that
because obj_reset_changes() was shadowing the fields import, we needed to
disambiguate one of the two in order to check against fields. Since fields is
a part of that method's API, I decided to change the import, which had a bunch
of fallout changes that aren't completely related, but necessary.

Change-Id: I5beb7d86fbcee712bb3c3b791b5ab37d90441d2a

commit_message:
Fix deprecated options in MySQL config

The "key_buffer_size" option has replaced the old "key_buffer".
Additionally set explicit TIMESTAMP values.

Change-Id: Iaa2aa6d3d68003c669fbef849acd892f6f40b393
Closes-Bug: 1405098

commit_message:
Add x509_sign provider to openssl module.

It adds the x509_sign provider in order to be able to sign a CSR. It
adds two parameters that are: infile and template that is the config
file. Private key used by the CA to sign the certificate is passed
using the configuration file. You can use it as follow:

  x509_sign { "/tmp/signed_req.pem":
      ensure   => present,
      template => "/tmp/ca_openssl.cnf",
      infile   => "/tmp/user_req_cert.pem"
  }

Change-Id: I9be9df731be3bf64333eff366aaf9eb27a27b72d
Implements: blueprint ssl-endpoints

commit_message:
Generalize the object relationships test

This adds a test_relationships_in_order() checker task that allows projects
to scan their object repositories and ensure that relationships between
objects are in order and consistent.

Change-Id: I71cdeb5786b8ea927823e1fbbadb374149c7708c

commit_message:
Generalize compatibility testing

This makes the test_obj_make_compatible() into a generalized thing that
scans the object repository and makes sure that, for every version between
X.0 and X.Y, obj.obj_make_compatible(target_version=version) works (i.e.
doesn't raise an exception).

Change-Id: I01efbf45d8df385bd245bee0c3cedc780fd4cd97

   opening brace, e.g. "\{text}"

commit_message:
Fix ubuntu_service_override ordering

Fixes resource ordering in tweaks::ubuntu_service_override to make
sure we do not leave any 'override' files.
Replaces tabs with spaces in ubuntu_service_override.pp
Added tweaks::ubuntu_service_override for cinder-volume in
openstack::cinder class.

Change-Id: I036cb65153029bb1a09be5eea2ee5bb4cbe97ae9
Closes-bug: #1421595
(cherry picked from commit 8994a8ad5e9767f1a7f84cf95b387e71bb39c6cf)

'}]
commit_message:
Update cinder $manage_volume condition for cinder VMDK

$manage_volume condition was improperly checking for the cinder role to
 deploy cinder-volume to. We need to deploy cinder-volume the same way
 as we do for ceph

add host param to cinder backend vmkd as it happens is
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/157004/

Change-Id: I9f615b88f6d22a902ed93f7a6e1eb84803991b34
Closes-Bug: 1410517

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-17 06:41:53.000000000', 'message': "Use haproxy's http-server-close by default

At load, haproxy begins accumulating a large number of connections to
backend services stuck in TIME_WAIT state. Eventually, this leads to
stalled requests to OpenStack API services. http-server-close solves
that problem.

Change-Id: Ie405fe2d384d9d8375f60ad2c3c9885f41fe6d49
Closes-Bug: 1413104
(cherry picked from commit 6c6bfc35f779774141274579b948280518f57e2d)
(cherry picked from commit a8417ef811919dbe7abee90eeb67f4ca7ede2935)

commit_message:
Use haproxy's http-server-close by default

At load, haproxy begins accumulating a large number of connections to
backend services stuck in TIME_WAIT state. Eventually, this leads to
stalled requests to OpenStack API services. http-server-close solves
that problem.


Change-Id: Ie405fe2d384d9d8375f60ad2c3c9885f41fe6d49
Closes-Bug: 1413104
(cherry picked from commit 6c6bfc35f779774141274579b948280518f57e2d)
(cherry picked from commit a8417ef811919dbe7abee90eeb67f4ca7ede2935)

commit_message:
Move metric capabilities into a single Resource

Previously, one call to /capabilities would result in potentially
several Capability objects being returned (through `list`),
and you had to check the value to know what type of capability
it was. This change brings that all together in one object and
sets the type of capabiltiy returned as a property on the object.

It now works like this:

>>> from openstack.metric.v1 import capabilities
>>> caps = capabilities.Capabilities().get(session)
>>> caps.aggregation_methods
['mean', 'max', 'avg']

Change-Id: Icee03330d42df8aeea11863eef7e4721d8311156

commit_message:
Retry installing apt packages by default

There are a number of tasks used to install apt packages. Some of the
tasks will retry on failure and others will not. These tasks are
susceptible to failure and so it makes sense that they retry if the
task fails.

This commit updates the apt tasks so that they all retry with the
default retries and delay values of 3 and 5 respectively. In addition
all the tasks will attempt to update the cache if it is older than
600 seconds.

Some of the apt tasks had the state set to latest, this has been
changed to present because upgrades should be handled by specific
upgrade tasks.

Closes-Bug: #1421238
Change-Id: I8c20c5c0a2ce87706a99734adcdf55c93efb405c

commit_message:
Fix security group setup when users_per_tenant is > 1

If there is more than one user per tenant, utils.iterate_per_tenants()
will handle only one user per tenant, leaving the others without
their secgroup context being setup. So instead we have to iterate
over all users.

The unit test was hiding this fault by using the users context
duplicated by "*2", making both copies being updated simultaneously.

Change-Id: Iea8624b272e422575cb7d297d4ff440f64a7b679
Closes-Bug: 1423607

commit_message:
Do not show topology page for the new environment

If environment is empty, topology tab doesn't make sense.
This fix hiding it in that case.

Change-Id: Id25f04ed77a15fdb730af3f719d8ad1c5a9401c7

commit_message:
Update guest VM OS recommendation in SAIO doc

The target development platform has changed to Ubuntu 14.04 [1].
This patch makes the suggested SAIO platform the same.

Also, remove pointer to wiki page for other platform install
instructions that either redirects back to this SAIO doc or
to another wike page and then a dead link.

[1] I0a96bcf692bb240f3ab5aab7fefd294a07735a83

DocImpact

Change-Id: I9f96104b5437c1f1f28f924c048ef83cf03338f4

commit_message:
Increase py26 timeouts for nova-stable

Seeing repeated timeouts on the current 40 minute limit for jobs
on nova for stable juno.  Increasing to 60.

Change-Id: I8f26714d696928b899b81cb5c2703f00e2185a96

commit_message:
Use oslo.i18n for translation

Remove gettextutils in favor of oslo.i18n suite for
internationalization purposes. Wrap murano.common.i18n around
oslo.i18n. Mark all logs messages of levels higher than
DEBUG for translation with _/_LI/_LW/_LE/_LC to conform with
oslo.i18n guidelines.

Change-Id: I09a2e2fc802e404f5c59fa4edd2a2124ad24101a
Implements: blueprint organize-translation

commit_message:
Unify logic that determines liveliness of DHCP agent

For DHCP agents sometimes it's not enough to check agent's last heartbeat
time because in its starting period the agent may fail to send state reports
because it's busy processing networks.
In rescheduling logic such DHCP agent is given additional time after start.
Additional time is proportional to amount of networks the agent is hosting.
Need to apply the same logic to DHCP agent scheduler to avoid a case
when starting agent is considered dead and a network gets more hosting
agents than configured.

Change-Id: I0fe6244c7d2ed42e4744351be34f251318322c54
Closes-Bug: #1417708

commit_message:
Data which evaluates to 'False' is now properly passed to context

Fixes a bug when the data being passed into the expression context was not
properly checked for being not-None which was causing the empty lists/dicts
or False booleans to be omitted from the context.

Change-Id: I56875f0847169ab8ed0fc29ea1400a1fa4ca2c2a

commit_message:
Restore CLI entry point and version in setup.cfg

During project toxification (commit c96200f) setup.py was modified
according to OpenStack standards and the entry_point and version
info were removed from it.
However, appropriate sections were not added into setup.cfg.
This commit puts them there, so CLI and package versioning works
properly again.

Change-Id: I1e2ed6513b4e4cd8d3dcc774fd456833dc7c79d5

commit_message:
Added retries in 'network_set_host' function

In concurrent transactions in 'network_set_host' function
could happen a deadlock or returned rows_updated value
could be equal to 0.

In these cases we should retry the transaction to get
another row and try to set the host again.

Closes-Bug: #1422610

Change-Id: I374b12e62f76810ffdb1e2d35af72a738ead5591

commit_message:
Split out BootstrapNode SoftwareConfig

This patch splits out the BootstrapNode config
such that alternate implementation (puppet for example)
can implement their own SoftwareConfig's via a nested stack.

This is controlled by the standard overcloud heat environment.

For os-apply-config deployments the implementation should work the
same as before.

For puppet deployments the implementation uses hiera metadata
to configure bootstrap_nodeid.

Change-Id: I691a9d7c474866038a5d47beab295899b5479d03

commit_message:
Change defaults test_sets in OSTF test.

Because simple mode is transferred to experimental status,
change the default values for OSTF tests. For compatibility
with existing code checks to  see, if mode is used
without HA, and in tests it is listed, then remove the
ha-tests.

Change-Id: Iff796e879b51686602ad182cdd1e5ccd23dd4403

commit_message:
Let HAProxy determine usefulness of TCP splicing

The "splice-auto" options causes HAProxy to evaluate splice() system
call performance using light heuristic, independently for requests and
responses. The possible gain of splicing depends on too many factors and
might be dependent on used hardware so there is no point in hardcoding
it.

Change-Id: I06e106eaacf9c67a9ef1582a37b5c46209fb0c2b
Closes-Bug: 1420710
(cherry picked from commit ea938a425423ec68174e10ef6de4c2fa4429304c)

Make import of oslo libraries namespaceless

commit_message:
Make "enabled" colume values display-friendly and consistent

Most boolean columes are displayed through yesno_filter
and capfirst_filter, but the changed field were not.

In addition, by using yesno_filter, the corresponding colums
are displayed with translated strings and it fixes I18N bug
at the same time.

The following columes are updated by this patch.

Identity -> Domains (enabled)
Identity -> Users (enabled)
Identity -> Groups (enabled)
Firewall -> Rules (enabled, audited)

Change-Id: I35eeed6addc8f58faa34bc990c758523e4830960
Closes-Bug: #1422074

commit_message:
Remove deprecated property of router_interface

Old property SUBNET_ID is not used in current code and may be deleted.
The resolving function was changed to support only one key in property
schema.

Change-Id: Id5057e6051e721616df4dc6496a6202372645db8

[{'created': '2015-02-17 22:32:05.000000000', 'message': 'heat-config-notify support deploy_signal_verb

The URL for deploy_signal_id is called with POST by default, however some
signals need to be called with PUT (specifically signals backed by swift
objects).

commit_message:
heat-config-notify support deploy_signal_verb

The URL for deploy_signal_id is called with POST by default, however some
signals need to be called with PUT (specifically signals backed by swift
objects).

This change uses the value of deploy_signal_verb for POST or PUT, using
POST by default.

Change-Id: I8c83fa34cad9b1e91abcfc7e26e04b21cdc9bde4
Partial-Blueprint: software-config-swift-signal

commit_message:
Mock link local allocator write so UT doesn't write a file

The UTs recently started writing a fip-linklocal-networks file in
test_l3_agent.  This is due to a recently added test.  This patch adds
a mock to it so that the file is not written.

Change-Id: I338a369fe25e64faa84cdec413d6bad7b315f890

commit_message:
libvirt: Adjust Nova to support FCP on System z systems

There are some platform specific changes needed to allow Nova to support
System z: the System z specific format of the device file paths, adding
and removing devices explicitely, and ignoring vHBAs which are offline.

Partial-Implements blueprint libvirt-kvm-systemz

Change-Id: Ica4938d9962bbb402e26dd47f0aea502ea0c4245

commit_message:
Snapshot of bootable volume goes in error state

If volume is not created from image, no glance
metadata would be available for that volume/snapshot
in volume glance metadata table. So simply catch
GlanceMetadataNotFound and do nothing.

Closes-Bug: #1413880
Change-Id: Ic3267d422912f94e966412859e2b8bddeddfb75f

commit_message:
Moved keystone settings in the ceilometer collector

Removed _connect abstract method as we can't assume the collector will
connect somewhere and should be handled by the collector himself.
Removed now useless state manager in orchestrator(handled by the storage
backend).
Kept the keystone instance in the orchestrator for future token
validation purpose.

Change-Id: I471ed1ad94345c83a637247d814a30b38743b100

commit_message:
Pinned oslo.messaging version

We're not using oslo_messaging namespace.
We need to fix this before moving to >=1.6.0.

Change-Id: Ib72c5be10a2e4e4ac2e6dc4076bf4ccdb92a59a0

commit_message:
Move auth_token into its own folder

In preparation for splitting auth_token into files we move everything
into its own folder and verify that it still works, and establish a
separate testing directory.

Change-Id: I4f3aad706e2e9fa1b984b022858adabb552258e2
Implements: bp refactor-extract-module

commit_message:
Be explicit about using /tmp for temporary datafiles

If TMPDIR is not set, different version of mktemp will behave
differently. To be sure, best to be explicit.

Change-Id: Id92eb4e5b833a1c0859a0c6d68cfc2f4e1f6977f

commit_message:
Make the dispatcher handler be an actual type

Instead of having the dispatcher target be a tuple
or a single callback, have it be an actual type with
comments as to what the types fields are and how they
are used.

This makes it more obvious as to what those fields are
and how they are used so that it is easier to understand
how the WBE engine and components work.

Change-Id: I5541ccd5a7aa6ae73ed9adceeac2c0524e2a1dc9

commit_message:
Email notifier returns false if self._smtp == None

When an email notifier is created and the initial smtp connection fails the
self._smtp variable is left set to None.  Now we detect that and try to
reconnect.

Change-Id: Ifbc30ee5339722357d86214b4d8c84e64dd703f7

commit_message:
Allow the periodic worker to take a periodic object(s)

Instead of having the periodic worker only take decorated
functions/methods allow it to take a new immutable object that
has the same information as the decorated method/functions (and
that object is now used internally to the worker) so that it is
easier to dynamically create periodic callables (without having
to create mini-methods that are decorated to work around this
limitation).

Change-Id: Icbaf0c321de91dee46a7bf44449ac5b94f86fdeb

commit_message:
Implement refresh as kwargs in get_volume_stats

When implementing the base driver "get_volume_stats" function, not all
drivers implemented 'refresh' as a kwarg. This can cause failures for any
code that simply invokes the following (assuming that refresh will default
to False -- which is does for 50+ drivers):

    driver.get_volume_stats()

This patch set updates the 7 drivers that did not implement refresh as a
kwarg so that the various driver implementations are consistent.

Closes-bug: 1423357
Change-Id: I6520155d1cbde4bf41573c170f4ea81815b5c1c2

commit_message:
Sort event-list by oldest first

Since event-list is log-like, it would be *much* friendlier
to users to sort by oldest first, especially for large
stacks where the events scroll.

This change adds sort_dir=asc to the event list query for
the CLI event-list command only.

Change-Id: I479e9ec36bf14a5f250348ca4279c508da23c2a2
Closes-Bug: #1420091

commit_message:
Provide additional detail if OAuth headers are missing

If WSGIPassAuthorization is not set correctly, the user gets back
an obscure message, since the code continues and tries to get
values from a None object.

This change brings a proper exception for this configuration issue
and lets the user know what to fix.

Closes-Bug: #1420121

Change-Id: Iee282383a67ec13b5bfb5267fe9d81124c5e289d

commit_message:
Allow Resource attributes to be updated

With Resource being a MutableMapping, it inherits an `update` method
like any mapping does. In the Connection layer, this would be really
useful when we want to be able to update properties on a Resource
based on dictionaries or named arguments users are calling proxy
methods with. However, since we override `update` to do our own idea
of updating, we lose that.

A specific example of where this is useful is that
object_store.set_*_metadata would work great if it could take named
arguments and set them on a resource, and then call `update`. The
following pseudocode explains:

    def set_metadata(container, **metadata):
        container.update_attrs(metadata)
        ...

    set_metadata(c, read_ACL="foo", write_ACL="bar")

This would result in those resource.props being set on the `c`, whereas
today we would have to look into the **metadata keys and values and send
them through setattr.

Change-Id: I1f7d71e7874ad39c353e299e3d4aac11c5e229e8

commit_message:
Mutate Resource via mapping instead of dict

resource.prop was doing all of its mutation of the parent Resource via
instance._attrs, i.e., directly modifying the attributes and working
around the MutableMapping magic methods where we've handled things like
the dirty list, which we then look at when doing calls like
Resource.update. Because we're bypassing that, we're not properly
sending the correct values in update calls for attributes that were
modified via their prop.

If we make resource.prop do its get/set/delete on the Resource instance
and let the Resource instance work with the underlying dictionary, the
dirty list is kept accurate regardless of how attributes were modified,
whether it's through creation of the object, prop update, or mapping
update.

Change-Id: I977ce898a4a7b8718d7d6a29470d51ab8a5dd674

commit_message:
Add Rules.from_dict classmethod

Many services currently construct a Rules instance from a dictionary in
their tests. It would be beneficial to them if they didn't have to
import oslo_policy._parser in order to parse a rule before passing it to
Rules.__init__. Adding a Rules.from_dict classmethod should satisfy the
need to create a Rules instance from a dictionary in tests.

Change-Id: I3d73059277c45d4852f842474c6f1d61daa349b8

commit_message:
Use assertTrue or assertFalse where appropriate

Previously we were using assertEqual(True, expected) or
assertEqual(False, exepected) instead of assertTrue or assertFalse
respectively. This simply updates the existing tests to follow the
common practice in oslo and OpenStack.

Change-Id: I05747a13533be00f7adc827276b833ae6aefd725

commit_message:
Fix the order of args to assertEqual in tests

The order of parameters needs to be (expected, actual) and many of the
tests in test_checks, test_parser, and test_policy were not following
that convention.

Closes-bug: 1277104
Change-Id: I2259972de4961bf9d5f9c6742d81eb083b770fba

commit_message:
Block novaclient 2.21

There is a bash completion bug in novaclient 2.21
which is causing nova volume-attach to fail so we
need to ban this release as it's also blowing
up gate jobs.

Change-Id: I8bebf3cf444522d66e1d4ac322642a1eea9e8441
Related-Bug: #1423695

commit_message:
Remove error logs for a common situation (non created ipsets)

The log message was initially added by me as part of a
iptables_firewall refactor.

Ipsets for empty IP address lists aren't currently created,
that means that we can't reference empty security groups
(as ipsets) via iptable rules, and that's a normal condition,
not an error.

Closes bug: #1421772
Change-Id: I6b1ae1fb505ce5e76ef8cf7ef7df38cff57e0000

commit_message:
Base launch instance wizard

- Setting up base launch instance wizard to enable parallel
  development on steps in the work flow.
- Adding business logic related code to openstack_dashboard
  project.
- Using Horizon's well-defined plug-in architecture to hook
  launch instance to Horizon.

Partially Implements: blueprint launch-instance-redesign

commit_message:
added dynamic cluster create flow

- added create_cluster_node flow factory function for creating a
  cluster node
- modified create_cluster flow factory function to call
  create_cluster_node for each cluster node
- modified neutron and nova fixtures to support testing for
  cluster create flow

Change-Id: I92aae38d71baeca9a84385813180703bbb9c2ece

As far as I can tell, get_state_from_hosts grabs all of /var/log, so having these logs in their own subdirectory should make them easier to find when debugging a CI failure.'}, {'account_id': 12459, 'date': '2015-01-19 20:25:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-01-20 02:45:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think the idea is good, however I think this is operationally setting a standard that not everyone may agree with.  Perhaps we should make this configurable with the default being /var/log/tripleo?'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-01-22 02:15:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Im inclined to agree with Julia. Im also going to nitpick on the default and proposed /var/log/os-servces.

Additionally, we catch a lot more than just openstack services with the rsyslog match line (kernel.log ends up in /var/log/tripleo for example). This was fine before because we were placing the results in /var/log but if were going to move this to a subdir we probably should improve our matching.'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2015-02-20 00:45:46.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

WRT to this change catching more than just openstack logs - that's true; but it's also true that our existing setup does the same, resulting in some logs going to (vor instance) /var/log/kern.log while some go to /var/log/kernel.log

I don't see a simple way to fix this; and making the directory configurable seems like it's going to take more brain than I'm willing to dedicate to this right now, so I'm going to abandon this change."}]

commit_message:
Put Openstack service logs into tripleo directory

Prior to this change, it was difficult for us to identify which files
under /var/log came from openstack services. Amongst other things, this
made it impossible to write log rotation policies which apply only to
the Openstack service logs.

This change moves the logs into their own directory, /var/log/tripleo

It's now easy for logrotate to apply special handling to these log files
without having to touch the system log rotate rules.

Change-Id: I8439ce29dd8a0dc8f68fbb1acee73ebdc07f9c25

commit_message:
Supress warning in cli methods that have sensetive output

All commands that have special output format (json, yaml, csv,
...) shouldn't print any warnings

remove import of deprecated novaclient.v1_1

Change-Id: I3f3e209887fa4201314d2210cfb73fe40f8a532d
Closes-bug: #1423696

commit_message:
Stop making devstack-dsvm-cells voting

devstack-dsvm-cells is broken, and blocking everything. We actually have
two jobs devstack-dsvm-cells and tempest-dsvm-cells.

Make devstack-dsvm-cells  non-voting to unwedge thing. Next step is to
re-evaluate running this job at all.

Remove gate-devstck-dsvm-cells jobs as we don't run non-voting gate
jobs.

Related-Bug: #1423695

Change-Id: Ieb8e5924e71a0bf68837258f2da49918a1285adc

What is the reasoning here?

There's no bugs, no updates on the spec for this change. I kinda understand it but in a very simplistic way, and I want to confirm if this code is actually fixing that. So, is this code fixing programmatic errors? Like in case someone updates the states.py setting a non-stable state as target? Or it's also fixing something that the user of Ironic could hit?"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-02-16 10:24:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Also, it pretty much looks like stable states == passive states (even in the docstring it says stable/passive).

So why calling it "stable" and not "passive" so it's more aligned with the spec, I mean, introducing another term for the same thing will make it more confusing.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-02-17 11:39:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

This LGTM, though I share Lucas' concerns as well"}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:39:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Lucas,

This is trying to prevent programming errors for people adding new states.  Without this patch it is easy for target to not be set to stable/passive state.

I can update the patch to use the term passive.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:44:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2

Ok thanks for clarifying. So it's to prevent programmatic errors which is fair enough!

So changing my vote here. Re: stable vs passive terminology, honestly I think stable is a better one. If people agree in updating the spec to use that term instead it would be nice. But I don't want to hold this patch on that. I will leave it open until we get some agreement on that.

But anyway, code-wise LGTM! thanks"}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-17 16:46:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

I have proposed patch to change term in spec from 'passive' to 'stable'

https://review.openstack.org/156655"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-02-17 19:21:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think that until the change to the spec is approved, this shouldn't get merged.

I also want to think about what this means for a generic fsm. The concept of 'stable' is something that we/Ironic is using. In fact, I think 'target' was added for Ironic too.

Maybe it needs a generic interface/dictionary so that attributes can be added.

Or maybe we should be subclassing?"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-02-17 19:35:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

I don't think this patch should be approved until the spec is updated. In case people disagree with renaming 'passive' to 'stable'. (Although I don't think there will be a problem, but still.)

wrt the fsm.py being part of a library, that work (to make it a library) has started [1] but it doesn't exist yet. In the meantime, I suspect it is fine to change it, and I am guessing we may end up subclassing it if/when we move to using the library.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141961/"}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-02-17 22:08:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-02-17 23:02:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Add concept of stable states to the state machine

Adding the concept of a 'stable' state.  When using add_state() only a
'stable' state can be used as a target.

Change-Id: I22ec4f4cbb855849e9a80b6a32ed01d1616958da

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-25 21:58:21.000000000', 'message': 'Move eventlet server options to a config section

Keystone can run in an eventlet server (keystone-all), or it can
run in a WSGI container (Apache Httpd). There are several
configuration options that are only used to configure the eventlet
server and are ignored when running in a WSGI container. Having
all the eventlet server options in the default section makes it
difficult for deployers to know what can be ignored when running
in WSGI mode. The options that are only used by the eventlet
server are moved into an [eventlet_server] section, and the SSL
options are moved into [eventlet_server_xml].

DocImpact

Change-Id: I6dd718c4d54056d0e29978f393ec45f7291f802d

commit_message:
Move eventlet server options to a config section

Keystone can run in an eventlet server (keystone-all), or it can
run in a WSGI container (Apache Httpd). There are several
configuration options that are only used to configure the eventlet
server and are ignored when running in a WSGI container. Having
all the eventlet server options in the default section makes it
difficult for deployers to know what can be ignored when running
in WSGI mode. The options that are only used by the eventlet
server are moved into an [eventlet_server] section, and the SSL
options are moved into [eventlet_server_ssl].

bp eventlet-server-config

Change-Id: I6dd718c4d54056d0e29978f393ec45f7291f802d

commit_message:
Add documentation of DIB_IMAGE_CACHE variable

It is an established convention to use DIB_IMAGE_CACHE in elements to
refer to the cache location. This convention has not been documented
in the README, unlike other element development practices. This change
adds documentation for DIB_IMAGE_CACHE both from an element user and
developer perspective.

This change was prompted by I76030654e7dfc7b7d4dfa87e082c14e7cee479b9

Change-Id: I6fcc2409450cdb45e5afcb292908fbaee1af258a

commit_message:
Remove Heat from example local.conf

Heat is provided in default devstack installations, and isn't required
in local.conf any more.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Heat/GettingStartedUsingDevstack#Heat_and_Devstack

Change-Id: I6bbb9a4cf16f6a859b83dbad79d07f022c93c5e1
Closes-Bug: 1423569

commit_message:
Switch to using oslo.log from library

This commit switches to using the oslo.log library instead of the
locally synced version from oslo-incubator. Also, since Tempest-lib
doesn't actually use oslo.config for anything except oslo.log now
that we're using it as an external lib let's remove oslo.config from
the requirements file.

Change-Id: Ia4f12b747643637d93bf6873563b6c34924c5bb0

The code looks good and works for me, but it has broken a couple of Selenium tests which should be fixed.

Also, I've realized that we show Password + Password confirmation field both for hidden and shown passwords. Looks a bit silly to me (what's the purpose of confirming the password which is clearly visible? It only makes sense when specifying email address, because a confirmation letter is usually sent to that address right after submitting the form - so you had to do right from the beginning). Might be well to get UX feedback on that.

I understand that it's not the proper place to notice the above fact, but someone should have said that somewhere :). Might be worth doing something with that, not necessarily in this patch."}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2015-01-08 19:46:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Improve robustness of network failover

In some cases when remove_network_from_dhcp_agent is called
concurrently by more than one neutron server it leads to unexpected
DB exception when NetworkDhcpAgentBinding is removed.
Need to avoid such case and make remove_networks_from_down_agents
method resistant to such issues by catching broad exception.

Change-Id: I653e200d89eb795ded742bb49420f09f66625587
Closes-Bug: #1417629

commit_message:
Provide independent disk size from image

The image should only specify the size of the image.  The backing disk
may be independent of this.  For instance a 5 GB image put on to a 20 GB
disk.

This change set allows for that independence in the specification.  Will
create the disk based on the overall requirements from the flavor.

Adds a change to the localdisk.py to support this.

Minor MTMS fix for the available nodes in the driver.

Change-Id: I16cd312acf2d7cf395c55f5cfae0bddaf991a6a9

commit_message:
Do not use urllib3 from requests

glanceclient is using the embedded version of urllib3 from
requests, which is removed from Debian (and Ubuntu), so
everything is failing over. This patch restores sanity.

Change-Id: Id6766e99cc522a21581c282739dc4f9c1840986f

commit_message:
Fix mock import in Python 3.2

The "from six.moves import mock" just fails in Python 3.2,
which is in Wheezy. This patch adds an except: statement,
which does the import in the old style, before commit
4fc793fce5a59feb8beab59178480414a4e1db25 changed it.

The Debian package which I maintain uses this patch already,
and it works in both Python 3.2 and 3.4. Please accept it
upstream, as I don't think it may hurt.

Change-Id: Id93c26240ae2951a4bbd2cf7900d85a49a7b20d6

There is an odd tradeoff here.

Too high -> the periodic sync_power_state job can block and timeout.
Too low -> we can inadvertantly knock over some (fragile) BMCs and require a hard-reset of the BMC (not the node) to unbrick it. This is really hard on operators.

Let's get some feedback from folks who are operating today (tripleo and onmetal teams) about what setting they use and why."}, {'account_id': 11929, 'date': '2014-11-11 14:46:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add documentation for the IPMI retry timeout option

It is difficult to have a universal default for the retry_timeout
option in the [impi] configuration section. This patch adds
documentation of the tradeoffs involved, while leaving the
conservative default in place.

Closes-Bug: 1383432
Change-Id: Ic7973cf7fee60cc817e5c0f5f9bfc84b3bca91c7

[{'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-02-08 18:52:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-02-08 18:52:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-08 18:56:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

- gate-magnum-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/86/153886/1/check/gate-magnum-python27/e4cbf7d/ : SUCCESS in 1m 17s'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-02-08 21:38:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi all,

I want to use this review to discuss how to implement the update-node-count BP. The goal is to allow users to scale up/down the kube cluster by updating the 'node_count' attribute of bay. This review shows an option to implement this.

Here is how it works. Basically, magnum reads the new node_count from request, and update the heat stack by passing the new node_count as a parameter (with other parameters unchanged). After that, heat will update the cluster accordingly. It seems that heat will understand the diff between the old cluster and new cluster, and update the deployed resources accordingly. Actually, some resources are updated in-place, while others are replaced with new resources.

An advantage of this approach is simple: it is straightforward to implement. A drawback is that heat will shutdown the cluster during update, which incurs service disruption. In addition, it seems that Heat will simply deleting all the VMs in the cluster and replacing them with a new set of VMs, which I am not sure if it is acceptable.

An alternative approach is to scale the kube cluster by using AutoScalingGroup ( http://docs.openstack.org/developer/heat/template_guide/openstack.html#OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup ), instead of ResourceGroup ( https://github.com/larsks/heat-kubernetes/blob/master/kubecluster.yaml#L291 ). This allows us to scale the particular set of resources instead of updating the whole stack. However, a roadblock is that the master node is not automatically updated after the scaling of the minion nodes, because this software config resource ( https://github.com/larsks/heat-kubernetes/blob/master/kubecluster.yaml#L184 ) is not updated automatically. We need to either manually update the master node or submit a patch to heat to fix that.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-02-08 22:07:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

clearly shutting down the whole cluster is suboptimal.  I wasn't aware resourcegroup behaved in that way.

We need to scale up using an autoscaling group with a parameter update.  I'm not quite sure how to trigger a change in the master node.  Try asking on #heat - I think this is a common question and maybe they have some ideas."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2015-02-08 23:05:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

tripleo are using ResourceGroup too, and there have been some recent fixes to stop specific actions from replacing the whole cluster (they should be backport to juno too).

Get in touch with Steve Hardy (shardy) or raise bugs if you're still having issues."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-09 04:11:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-02-09 23:43:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My preference is to use Heat for this feature, and if we find it suboptimal, then propose enhancements to Heat to accommodate. This way we avoid re-implementing scaling group implementation in Magnum.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-02-09 23:55:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Please try using replacement_policy: auto for the OS::Neutron::Port resources in the resource group's kubenode.yaml file."}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-02-11 05:01:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It also looks like this patch may need to be rebased.'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-02-12 05:10:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-12 05:16:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

After further testing of this features, it seems that Heat still attempts to replace the master node on bay update. The reason is that the master node is using user_data [1] to bootstrap the VM. Unfortunately, a bay update has to change the user_data, which causes the master node to be replaced.

A straightforward solution is to move all the bootstrapping scripts from user_data to SoftwareDeployments [2]. However, SoftwareDeployments introduces additional image dependencies [3], which I am not sure if it is acceptable. I appreciate if anyone can comment on that. Thanks.

[1] https://github.com/stackforge/magnum/blob/master/etc/magnum/templates/heat-kubernetes/kubecluster.yaml#L270
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/heat/template_guide/openstack.html#OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployment
[3] https://github.com/openstack/heat-templates/tree/master/hot/software-config/elements'}]

[{'created': '2015-01-22 10:19:10.000000000', 'message': 'Print JSON-compatible booleans

Given os-apply-config takes a JSON file as input and prints JSON-style
strings not Python ones, Booleans present an anomaly.

These are printed using `str(config)`, resulting in "True" and "False"
rather than the lowercase and JSON-compatible "true" and "false". This
patch corrects this.

There is some risk of breaking users but it should be trivial for them
to fix their scripts. As I write this, o-a-c is at 0.1.28, so we're

to make all output JSON-compatible.

Change-Id: Ib41d3b01656fc7afc4911fd78ba7c1116aa9b1c9
'}]
commit_message:
Print JSON-compatible booleans

Given os-apply-config takes a JSON file as input and prints JSON-style
strings not Python ones, Booleans present an anomaly.

These are printed using `str(config)`, resulting in "True" and "False"
rather than the lowercase and JSON-compatible "true" and "false". This
patch corrects this.

There is some risk of breaking users but it should be trivial for them
to fix their scripts. As I write this, o-a-c is at 0.1.28, so we're
allowed breaking changes and I believe this is the last change required
to make all output JSON-compatible.

Change-Id: Ib41d3b01656fc7afc4911fd78ba7c1116aa9b1c9

'}, {'created': '2015-01-23 06:43:55.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Check session before image upload

Uploading an image to vSphere backend without checking the session
results broken pipe socket error. When this happens, glance-api
sends a 400 response because the IOError is not handled by the
store.

We address this issue by :-
1. Checking if session is authenticated before adding the image.
2. Handle IOError and look into the response code.

Closes-Bug: #1402354

Change-Id: I66b6dfddfb2ddd089488f3f79f3917fd69739fc9

commit_message:
Check VMware session before uploading image

Uploading an image to vSphere backend without checking the session
results in broken pipe socket error. When this happens, glance-api
sends a 400 response because the IOError is not handled by the
store.

We address this issue by :-
1. Checking if session is authenticated before uploading the image.
2. Handle IOError and check the response code.

Closes-Bug: #1402354

Change-Id: I66b6dfddfb2ddd089488f3f79f3917fd69739fc9

commit_message:
Add non-voting job for Nova V2.1 API with neutron

'tempest-dsvm-nova-v21-full' job tests Nova V2.1 API with nova-network.
It runs all tempest nova v2 tests by changing the API endpoint from V2
to v2.1

There are many tests in Tempest which runs with neutron only and interact
with nova also for server request etc. Some of those tests fails when
running those against V2.1 due to strong input validation.
ex- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151117/

So it is important to test Nova V2.1 API with neutron to keep
API stability for nova-network as well as with neutron.

This job will gets triggered on specific below changes only
-/nova/network/neutronv2
-/nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/
-/nova/api/openstack/compute/schemas/v3/
-/tempest/api/network

This patch adds a new non-voting job to run tempest tests
for above mentioned changes with Nova v2.1 and neutron.

Change-Id: I8aa6f79e9349c1cae1307a687c9c0dfca0508f7f

commit_message:
Remove check job from tripleo-puppet-elements

This removes the check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-ha
from tripleo-puppet-elements changes. This should save us
some resources because this check job doesn't provided
any coverage on tripleo-puppet-elements.

commit_message:
Update sample config file

This takes into account a few changes that have modified the
sample config.

1) Handle SSL termination
   I76462db9c01a130964844207e375bd35359694f7
2) federated domains
   I84c95a0abe3f4c4bbe2b785fd773f54e3384f5ce
3) use oslo.log
   0f61b11141baff243d0e4c10b3dcb612584f7426

[{'created': '2014-10-24 18:21:18.000000000', 'message': 'modify events sql schema to reduce empty columns

in current design, three columns in Trait table are always empty.
this adds size to each row. since we are already checking for type
of value, we should just drop the items into their own tables.

this patch:
- moves trait table to four smaller tables similar to metadata
- maps traits to dict-like attribute in events model.
- bulk inserts traits

this patch aims to improve write and read performance.

commit_message:
modify events sql schema to reduce empty columns

in current design, three columns in Trait table are always empty.
this adds size to each row. since we are already checking for type
of value, we should just drop the items into their own tables.

this patch:
- moves trait table to four smaller tables similar to metadata
- does not map traits to dict-like attribute in events model as
  query performance is horrible.
- bulk inserts traits

this patch aims to improve write performance.

Closes-Bug: #1381736
Change-Id: I2bd4c16b57fe2c1ad67646ccd4417078f0f0f734

commit_message:
Updates training guides jobs

The training jobs get reorganized completely:
* XML files will only be run on Icehouse branch, master branch will go
  to RST files and generate slides (PDF, html).
* Stop translating the project.
* Add slides jobs that only runs on master and a possible icehouse
  branch

Change-Id: Iefb4f254e14e977333c23817d157c0995c002c6b

commit_message:
Add slides tox environment

Add slides tox environment for building RST based slides. This tox
environment needs to be enhanced moving forward. For now it includes
the doc8 test to test RST and txt files. Also setup doc8 testing.

Change-Id: I76e0d235b9ee89c8de8033a7119e34cbcf1f0ddd
